Question 2

What is the role of the stochastic error term \(u_{i}\) in regression analysis? What is the difference between the stochastic error term \(u_{i}\) and the residual, \(\hat{u}_{i}\)?

The stochastic error term \(u_{i}\) is the effect of many small (so small we are unable to effectively model them) effects on the variable, or the result of pure random variation in the dependent variable.

The residual \(\hat{u}_{i}\) is the stochastic error term. This will include any over/underestimate because of differences between the population and estimated parameters â€“ and can be smaller or larger than the stochastic error term.

\[\begin{equation*} \frac{\partial RSS}{\partial \hat{\beta}_{2}}=2\hat{\beta}_{2}\sum_{i=1}^{N}{X^2}-2\sum_{i=1}^{N}{XY}+2\hat{\beta}_{1}\sum_{i=1}^{N}{X}=0 \end{equation*}\]

Derive \(\hat{\beta}_{1}\) and \(\hat{\beta}_{2}\) mathematically using the first order conditions.

\(\sum_{i=1}^{N}{X}=n \bar{X}\)
